1927. 
<taxonomicName id="8DDC4D70FFFBFFBAFF709EF86B2B7FB1" authority="PLUMMER" authorityName="PLUMMER" box="[218,550,700,722]" class="Nodosariata" family="Lagenidae" genus="Cristellaria" kingdom="Chromista" order="Nodosariida" pageId="22" pageNumber="36" phylum="Foraminifera" rank="species" species="longiformis">
<emphasis id="78A8EAE1FFFBFFBAFF709EF868B27FB0" box="[218,447,700,721]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="36">Cristellaria longiformis</emphasis>
PLUMMER
</taxonomicName>
, p. 102, pl. 13, fig. 4. 15.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4A6336F3FFFBFFBAFF3D9EB26B017E49" blockId="22.[151,756,700,808]" pageId="22" pageNumber="36">
1976. 
<taxonomicName id="8DDC4D70FFFBFFBAFF709EB26B687E6A" authority="(PLUMMER)" baseAuthorityName="PLUMMER" box="[218,613,758,779]" class="Nodosariata" family="Vaginulinidae" genus="Vaginulinopsis" kingdom="Chromista" order="Vaginulinida" pageId="22" pageNumber="36" phylum="Foraminifera" rank="species" species="longiforma">
<emphasis id="78A8EAE1FFFBFFBAFF709EB268EE7E6A" box="[218,483,758,779]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="36">Vaginulinopsis longiforma</emphasis>
(PLUMMER)
</taxonomicName>
.- AUBERT &amp; BERGGREN, p. 418, p1. 4, fig. 5.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="02C66578FFFBFFBAFF3D9F096B3A7964" pageId="22" pageNumber="36" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="4A6336F3FFFBFFBAFF3D9F09684C7EE4" blockId="22.[151,756,845,1029]" pageId="22" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis id="78A8EAE1FFFBFFBAFF3D9F0968057E04" bold="true" box="[151,264,845,869]" pageId="22" pageNumber="36">Remarks:</emphasis>
It is distinguished by thin sutures in the median portion.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4A6336F3FFFBFFBAFF3D9FC96B3A7964" blockId="22.[151,756,845,1029]" pageId="22" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis id="78A8EAE1FFFBFFBAFF3D9FC968D87EC4" bold="true" box="[151,469,909,933]" pageId="22" pageNumber="36">Stratigraphic distribution:</emphasis>
It is recorded in the Paleocene in 
<collectingCountry id="32CB7663FFFBFFBAFE889FE968797EA4" box="[290,372,941,965]" name="Tunisia" pageId="22" pageNumber="36">Tunisia</collectingCountry>
, Morroco and 
<collectingCountry id="32CB7663FFFBFFBAFDA09FE96B547EA4" box="[522,601,941,965]" name="Angola" pageId="22" pageNumber="36">Angola</collectingCountry>
by BERGGREN &amp; AUBERT (1975). It is recorded in the Sudr Chalk and Esna Shale of the Esh El Mallaha area.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
